      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The data come from annual data on Gallup's polling on the public's sense of the national crime situation.  This variable is the percent of the public who say that there is more crime now than 12 months ago.  The other data is FBI crime statistics on annual homocide rate in the US.  The data was prepared by setting the Year as a chronologically sorted DatetimeIndex.  This ensured the data was correctly ordered by time, which is crucial for all subsequent time series operations. The frequency was standardized to Annual Start (AS, or YS-JAN), guaranteeing a continuous annual time series from 1989 to 2023.\n",
        "\n",
        "TECHNICAL NOTE 1:  I am assuming you are working in Colab and that you have created a spreadsheet of your time series data -- and you have downloaded your spreadsheet as a CSV onto your computer.  The code below will run and create a little button called \"Choose Files\" (you may have to scroll down to see it) - and when you click on that button, you can find your CSV on your computer and it will upload.\n",
        "\n",
        "TECHNICAL NOTE 2: NOTE that YOU have to specify the \"parse_dates=['YOURTIMEVARIABLE']\" and YOU have to specify the \"index_col='YOURTIMEVARIABLE'\" too ... so make sure to put the right name of your TIME variable there (whether is it \"Year\" or \"Month\" or \"Quarter\", etc).\n",
        "\n",
        "TECHNICAL NOTE 3: NOTE that YOU also have to specify the frquency of your time variable, in this case, I selected AS for \"Annual Series\", e.g., \"df = df.asfreq('AS')\"  You may need to pick something else, if you have Monthly data, then you would pick \"MS\" for Monthly Series."
      ],
