    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The first regression uses the possibly non-stationary level data to predict the public's perception of More Crime (Y) using the Homicide Rate (X) and a time trend.  As we would expect, it looks like the variables are strongly connected, with each additional homocide out of 100,000 being associated with on average, 8.4 percent of the public thinking crime has grown in the last year.  Although the Rsq is relatively high (0.67), the model may still be flawed.  The Durbin-Watson statistic of 0.83 is relatively close to 0, indicating significant positive autocorrelation in the residuals.  This strongly suggests a possibly misspecified model and we may also have non-stationary data too."
