    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "To achieve stationarity, the data was transformed using the first differences.  The plot \"Differenced Series\" visually confirms that the annual trend had been removed -- and the two series appear to sync up.  The second regression is then run on this hopefully stationary data, linking the change in Homicide Rate to the change in More Crime.  This model appears much more valid: the Durbin-Watson statistic improved significantly to 2.67, which is close to the ideal value of 2 (indicating little to no autocorrelation). Crucially, the coefficient for change in homocide rate is 7.3 (p<.01), and therefore, highly significant.  This appears to demonstrate that the year-to-year change in the Homicide Rate is a very strong predictor of the year-to-year change in the public's perception of crime.  The Rsq is much worse in this difference model than in the previous model, but that is expected, by virtue of the difference transformation."
